# THE BLOODLINE SHE DOESN'T KNOW
### *What the Maris Wyn Folio Changes*

**AT A GLANCE:** Arc 2–3 · Levels 7–12 · Subplot · Hidden until Ironclad Undercroft

---

## THE SITUATION

Commander Elyndra of the Sentinel Order has been the organization's self-made leader for forty years. She rose through merit, hard work, and two centuries of tactical learning. She is the commander because she is the best person for the job — this is her understanding of herself, and it is also accurate.

She is also, unknown to herself, a descendant of House Wyn — one of the five Founding bloodlines whose representatives are required for the Crown reforging. Her entire sense of herself as self-made is about to receive information she did not ask for and cannot unknow.

This quest is not about the information. It is about Elyndra's reaction to it. The DM's job is to play that reaction with full honesty.

---

## BACKGROUND — THE MARIS WYN FOLIO

House Wyn was one of Aeloria's five Founding bloodlines. Unlike the Valemont, Thessal, Drakor, and Caldris lines — which have reasonably well-documented descendants — the Wyn bloodline was deliberately scattered following the Night of Broken Glass. Caedric's agents, understanding the reforging's bloodline requirements, made a quiet priority of ending or obscuring the Wyn line. Not with open killing — that would be noticed — but with records that disappeared, identities that were rerouted, archives that were moved or sealed.

The Maris Wyn folio is a genealogical record commissioned by Archpriest Maris of the Wyn family temple two generations ago — a private family history, kept outside the main archives precisely because Maris did not trust the political climate with complete Wyn bloodline records. It documents the scattered descendants across four generations, following bloodlines that deliberately changed names, crossed racial lines, and moved jurisdictions.

One of those lines ends with Elyndra.

The specific descent: Elyndra's maternal grandmother was born Sora Wyn, a minor branch of the Wyn family, who emigrated to the Veilwood under the name Sora Veil-Keth following her family's dispersal. She never told her daughter. Her daughter never told Elyndra. The Sentinel Order's records show Elyndra's family as Sylvaran elves of moderate lineage — which is true, as far as it goes. It simply omits one generation's origins.

The folio ended up in the Ironclad Undercroft because the Darian Empire's Historical Acquisition Division — a polite name for the Imperial archive-gathering operation — swept Wyn family records as part of a broader genealogical census forty years ago. The folio was catalogued, cross-indexed, and filed. Nobody at the Empire's level connected it to the Sentinel Order commander. Why would they?

---

## THE DISCOVERY SCENE

The folio is in the Undercroft's Records Wing, Shelf 7, under "Wyn Family — Dispersal Documentation." It is not hidden — it is simply filed correctly in an archive with thirty thousand documents. Finding it requires either knowing what to look for (players who have been briefed on the reforging's bloodline requirements and are specifically searching for Wyn descendants) or a successful DC 17 Investigation check while conducting general research in the Undercroft.

The folio itself is a leather-bound document, 40 pages, in a formal genealogical hand. The Wyn bloodline section is on pages 31–34. A successful DC 12 History check is enough to understand its significance. A successful DC 15 History or Arcana check allows a player to confirm the genealogical chain's completeness — this is not ambiguous documentation. The chain is well-evidenced.

**How players bring it to Elyndra:** This should not be casual. The players have, in their hands, information that is going to fundamentally alter how their most important intelligence ally understands herself. They should feel that weight before the scene. The DM can give a moment here — "You're holding a document that tells you something significant about someone you know. What do you do?" — before moving to the encounter.

---

## ELYNDRA'S REACTION

She reads it twice.

This is the first thing to note: she does not react while reading. Her face does its operational thing — careful, neutral, processing. She reads the first time quickly; she reads the second time slowly, following the genealogical chain page by page. Players who make a DC 14 Insight check during this will notice that her hands have gone very still on the document. Not rigid — still, the way something is still when you are not sure what to do with it yet.

When she puts the folio down, she does not immediately speak.

The silence is real. It is not performed or theatrical. She is doing something internal that is taking a moment — the specific work of integrating information that rearranges a significant piece of how you understand yourself. She has been the Sentinel Order's self-made commander for forty years. She became commander because she was the best at the work, not because of blood. That is a specific identity. This document does not take that identity away. But it adds something to it that she did not choose and did not earn, and she is deciding what to do with that.

When she speaks, she says: "How certain is the genealogical chain?"

This is not a hope that it might be wrong. It is the first question a rigorous person asks because rigor is what she has. She needs to know whether this is confirmed or probable. The answer — if players have made the DC 15 check — is confirmed. She absorbs this.

Then: "I'll need a day."

She does not dismiss the players coldly. She thanks them, in specific and genuine terms, for bringing this to her rather than using it as leverage. She asks them to leave her with the folio for now. She will come to them.

**What "a day" looks like:** She is not visibly different when she returns. She has done the work privately, which is how she does everything important. But players who have made multiple Insight checks around Elyndra over the campaign will notice a fractional shift: she is slightly more deliberate than usual. As if she is double-checking herself. She has been running on forty years of self-knowledge that just got footnoted, and she is adjusting her calibration.

---

## THE ADJUSTMENT PERIOD

Over the next several sessions, one specific behavioral tell emerges: when Elyndra is about to state something with certainty — a tactical assessment, a judgment call, an intelligence conclusion — she pauses a half-beat longer than before. Not visibly uncertain. Just: checking. The kind of checking you do when you have just learned that one thing you thought was fully known had a piece you didn't have access to.

She does not become less effective. Her tactical judgment does not diminish. But the way she holds her own authority has changed slightly — it is more considered, less automatic. Players who have been with her long enough to know her baseline will notice this. She will not acknowledge it if asked directly; if pressed gently, she will say: "I'm verifying my reasoning more carefully than I was. That's not a bad thing."

---

## WHAT THIS MEANS FOR THE REFORGING

She is now confirmed as one of the five. This changes the reforging's feasibility significantly — the Wyn representative was the hardest position to fill, with the bloodline deliberately scattered.

**Whether she contributes willingly or must be asked:**

She will not volunteer. She will not walk into the planning conversation and announce herself. She will wait, for reasons she does not fully articulate, until the bloodline requirement for Wyn comes up — either because players are discussing it, or because the ritual planning reaches the point where her name is the answer. She wants to be asked, not because she needs the ceremony of it, but because contributing because you were needed is a different thing than contributing because you arrived with the right blood. She wants it to be a decision.

When she is asked, she says: "Yes." One word. No hesitation.

Her specific sacrifice in the ritual — the clearest memory she holds of the person she was before she became the Sentinel Order's commander — is something she has not fully reckoned with yet. She knows what she will have to give. She does not entirely know what losing access to that feeling will mean. The scene in which she realizes this is available to players who ask her about the ritual's costs after she has agreed; she will be honest that she knows and she has decided and she is still deciding how to hold it.

---

## COMPLICATIONS

**If Elyndra resents the discovery:** This is a valid way to play this, and some players may expect it. She does not resent the players — they found something real and brought it to her, which is correct behavior. What she is allowed to feel something complicated about is the discovery itself: the forty years of self-construction that had a foundation she wasn't told about. She is allowed to be quietly, briefly angry at her grandmother's silence. She may express this obliquely, once, and then not again.

**If a player tells her before the evidence is confirmed:** She stops them. She is not angry. She says, carefully, "If you're going to tell me something about my bloodline, I need you to be certain. Come back when you are." She is not putting her head in the sand — she is refusing to be unsettled by a possibility when certainty is achievable. This is her being rigorous. The players should go confirm and then return.

---

## RESOLUTION PATHS

**Elyndra accepts:** She takes a day. She returns. She is the Wyn bloodline representative. The Sentinel Order's cooperation at the ritual deepens — she is not just the commander helping a player mission, she is a participant in the thing the Sentinel Order was founded to enable. This distinction matters to her. She will mention it once and then not again.

**Elyndra refuses initially, then accepts:** She may say, initially, "I'll need to think about whether this changes what I'm willing to do." This is not doubt about the cause — it is her need to decide, rather than be assigned. Give her the space. She comes back in a session or two. The acceptance, when it comes, is more grounded for having been chosen from still ground rather than from surprise.

**Elyndra asks players not to tell anyone yet:** She wants a specific amount of time — perhaps a week, perhaps until after one particular thing is resolved — before this is known more broadly. She is not ashamed. She is being careful about a piece of information that will change how people look at her, and she wants to be on steady ground when it does. Players who honor this request earn something specific: the version of Elyndra who trusts them with what she isn't ready for yet.

---

## REWARDS

**Elyndra's full confidence:** Not just cooperation — confidence. She begins briefing players on things she has been holding back: pieces of intelligence she judged too sensitive for people who were still proving themselves, assessments she had not shared because they required trust to give and receive. The archive access deepens. Her briefings become more complete.

**Sentinel Order cooperation on a deeper level:** The Order's 87 Sentinels have a different relationship to a mission when their commander has personal stakes in it. Nothing announces this — it is not a policy change. It is a quality of commitment that players who have been in the field with Sentinels before will notice.

**One additional piece of Archive access:** Elyndra previously kept one section of the Archive restricted — the complete documentation of the Founding bloodlines' dispersal post-Night of Broken Glass. She restricted it because the information could be used to find or threaten the remaining bloodline members. Now that the players have already found the relevant piece, she opens it. It contains, among other things, additional intelligence about the Caldris and Thessal bloodline dispersals that could accelerate finding Cale and Selene.

---

## DM NOTES

Elyndra's greatness has always been that she built it herself. That is her identity and it is accurate. This discovery does not take that away — she is still the person who built the thing. But it adds a footnote to the foundation that she didn't write, and that addition does something to how a rigorous person holds their own history.

The scene should not be dramatic. It should be quiet. She reads. She is still. She asks one question. She asks for a day. The players who understand Elyndra will understand that this is a significant reaction from her, that the stillness and the single-day request represent something she is taking seriously. The DM should not underscore it with music cues or charged language. Trust the character to land the weight.

The gift of this scene, played well, is that the players watch someone they respect do the work of integrating difficult information with complete honesty and no performance. That is Elyndra at her fullest.
